      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1094">
               <p>Son of a zealous dissenting minister, Humphreys studied at Deptford Academy with
                  this ministry in view (<date from="1733" to="1739">1733–39</date>). Converted by
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName> he
                  began preaching in his home town of <placeName>Burford, Oxfordshire</placeName> in
                     <date when="1738">1738</date>, while on summer vacation. He formed a religious
                  society at <placeName>Deptford</placeName> for <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName>&apos;s converts that
                  fall. These activities led to his expulsion from Deptford Academy, so he moved to
                  study with <persName>John Eames</persName> in Moorfields, where he became friends
                  with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>. In <date
                     when="1740-09">Sept. 1740</date> he began to preach at the Foundery, and to
                  serve as <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s
                  pastoral assistant (<persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  called him &apos;the first lay preacher that assisted me in
                     <placeName>England</placeName> in <date when="1738">1738</date>&apos;). Within
                  about a year Humphreys recognized his divergence from <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s Arminianism, and joined
                  forces with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName>.
                  This relationship was also short lived; by <date when="1744">1744</date> Humphreys
                  had gone independent. He eventually received first Presbyterian and then (in <date
                     when="1751">1751</date>) Anglican ordination, and ended his career as rector of
                     <placeName>North Stoke and Ellisfield</placeName>—now disenchanted with the
                  evangelical movement. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 202–3; <hi
                     rend="italic">CCEd</hi>; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 582; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 170.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
